1
00:00:11,212 --> 00:00:12,980
STUDENT: Hey, Philip.
PHILIP: Hey, dude.

2
00:00:13,047 --> 00:00:14,948
STUDENT: What's up?
Did you pass that midterm?
PHILIP: Not really.

3
00:00:15,015 --> 00:00:17,485
WOMAN: Hey, Philip.
MAN: Hey, what's up, Phil?

4
00:00:23,291 --> 00:00:24,525
MEGAN: Thanks for lunch.

5
00:00:24,592 --> 00:00:26,194
I'm really glad you guys
got to see the new clinic.

6
00:00:26,260 --> 00:00:27,461
MOM: Are you kidding?

7
00:00:27,528 --> 00:00:29,597
Think we'd come to Boston
and not see our girl?

8
00:00:29,663 --> 00:00:32,566
We're so proud of you.

9
00:00:32,633 --> 00:00:35,103
Hey, Phil, I need your
help on my cadaver.
Okay.

10
00:00:35,169 --> 00:00:37,705
I've been trying for, like,
six hours to find the
posterior thoracic nerve,

11
00:00:37,771 --> 00:00:40,674
and if I don't dig it up soon,
Lenhoff is gonna cut me open.

12
00:00:40,741 --> 00:00:44,678
Yeah, I know. Posterior
thoracic is a bitch. Um,
I need, I need... Janet!

13
00:00:44,745 --> 00:00:46,914
Janet, love,
we need you.
Come here.

14
00:00:46,980 --> 00:00:48,682
Why don't I like
the sound of that?

15
00:00:48,749 --> 00:00:50,151
It's all in the interest
of science, dear.

16
00:00:50,218 --> 00:00:51,385
Trust me?
Sure.

17
00:00:51,452 --> 00:00:54,922
Put your left hand up.
Tom, pay attention.

18
00:00:54,988 --> 00:00:57,225
You just dig behind...
Sorry my hands are cold.

19
00:00:57,291 --> 00:01:01,562
Dig behind the scalenus
medius, then you move aside
the brachial plexus,

20
00:01:01,629 --> 00:01:05,166
and then slide down
to the serratus anterior.

21
00:01:05,233 --> 00:01:07,968
And there you have it.
Posterior thoracic.

22
00:01:08,035 --> 00:01:09,069
You finished, Philip?

23
00:01:10,204 --> 00:01:12,673
Yes. I thank you.

24
00:01:12,740 --> 00:01:14,842
Science thanks you.
Tom here thanks you.

25
00:01:14,908 --> 00:01:16,043
I thank you.

26
00:01:16,110 --> 00:01:17,611
All right, you guys.
I gotta go study, okay?

27
00:01:17,678 --> 00:01:19,513
TOM: Sure.
Bye.

28
00:01:21,815 --> 00:01:24,285
Any thoughts on why we're
seeing shortness of breath,

29
00:01:24,352 --> 00:01:26,520
lethargy and dizziness
in a 7-year-old?

30
00:01:26,587 --> 00:01:28,522
Eisenmenger Syndrome.

31
00:01:28,589 --> 00:01:30,824
I mean, that would go with
the pulmonary hypertension.

32
00:01:30,891 --> 00:01:33,294
DR. JANEWAY: That's a bit
of a leap, Mr. Markoff.

33
00:01:33,361 --> 00:01:36,230
But assuming your
hypothesis is correct,

34
00:01:36,297 --> 00:01:38,199
then why are we seeing
the low heart rate,

35
00:01:38,266 --> 00:01:41,335
the diminished reflex
and a lack of affect?

36
00:01:41,402 --> 00:01:45,139
Perhaps the fact
that a 7-year-old
boy is alone

37
00:01:45,206 --> 00:01:48,108
and his parents wouldn't
bother to be with him
when he's in the hospital.

38
00:01:48,176 --> 00:01:50,678
Hmm.
Personalizing, Philip?

39
00:01:50,744 --> 00:01:52,180
No, sir.

40
00:01:52,246 --> 00:01:53,881
BOY'S MOM:
Here you are, baby.

41
00:01:53,947 --> 00:01:57,351
I had to go all the way
to the CVS on Commonwealth
to get you the cherry kind.

42
00:01:57,418 --> 00:01:59,753
It'll be right here waiting
for you when you wake up.

43
00:02:00,921 --> 00:02:02,690
There's a lesson for you all.

44
00:02:02,756 --> 00:02:04,725
Things are not always
what they appear to be,

45
00:02:04,792 --> 00:02:07,828
and even the
remarkable Mr. Markoff

46
00:02:07,895 --> 00:02:09,330
isn't perfect.

47
00:02:11,131 --> 00:02:12,933
All right, guys.
Next patient.

48
00:02:16,136 --> 00:02:17,605
I only torture you,

49
00:02:17,671 --> 00:02:20,874
because when every major
hospital comes clamoring

50
00:02:20,941 --> 00:02:22,876
for you to do your
residency with them,

51
00:02:22,943 --> 00:02:25,879
I want you to realize
that this place

52
00:02:25,946 --> 00:02:30,218
